05406nam a22009495i 9780520905993DE-B159720230529094047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230529t19781978cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97805209059937 a10.1525/97805209059932doi  a(DE-B1597)520534  a(OCoLC)609849878  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPR3533 7aLIT0041202bisacsh04a828.6091 aBrady, Frank, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSamuel Johnson :bSelected Poetry and Prose /cWilliam Wimsatt, Frank Brady. 1aBerkeley, CA : bUniversity of California Press, c[1978] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (656 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction. Samuel Johnson (1709-1784): A Calendar Of His Career -- tBibliographical Note -- tLetters -- tPoems -- tThe History of Rasselas, Prince of Abyssinia -- tSelections from The Rambler -- tSelections from The Idler -- tPreface to A Dictionary of the English Language -- tPreface to The Plays of William Shakespeare -- tLives of the Poets0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is a major new selection of Samuel Johnson's best work, delightfully introduced by W. K. Wimsatt and scrupulously annotated by Frank Brady and Mr. Wimsatt.Samuel Johnson, the only writer in English since the Renaissance to give his name to a literary period, was the center of English letters in his time. He was Dictionary Johnson, the lexicographer who had single-handedly settled the English language (it was hoped) on a firm basis; he was the author of a handful of fine poems, including two of the most remarkable satires of the century; he was a moralist whose Rambler and Idler essays, and novel-of-ideas Rasselas, provided a searching view of men and matters. And in his final years he produced his greatest work, that extraordinary combination of biography and criticism which came to be known as the Lives of the Poets.This first extensive anthology of Johnson's writings to be published in many years emphasizes Johnson the writer. It responds to those aspects of Johnson's work of special interest to modern readers. It comprises a selection of Johnson's letters, all of his major poems (including London), Rasselas, twenty-one Rambler, nineteen Idlers, the Prefaces to the Dictionary and to the edition of Shakespeare, and the following Lives of the Poets: Cowley, Milton, Swift, Pope, Savage, Collins, and Gray. All these works are extensively annotated and printed complete. Mr. Wimsatt, one of the outstanding Johnsonians of this century, provides in his Introduction a clear, connected biographical account of Johnson, stressing his writings. An up-to-date bibliography is also included. Johnson's varied accomplishments—as poet, as moralist, as biographer, as critic—are all amply represented.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aEnglish poetryy18th century. 0aEnglish prose literaturey18th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / English, Irish, Scottish, Welsh.2bisacsh  a18th century.  aaesthetics.  abritish literature.  aclassics.  acollins.  acorrespondence.  acowley.  adictionary.  adrama.  aenglish language.  agray.  aidler.  ajohnson on shakespeare.  aletters.  alexicography.  alinguistics.  aliterary criticism.  aliterary theory.  alives of the poets.  alondon poem.  amillion.  anature on man.  apoetry.  apope.  apreface to the dictionary.  arambler.  arasselas.  asatire.  asavage.  asocial commentary.  aswift.1 aBrady, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWimsatt, W. K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWimsatt, William, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc